  <danish_publication>Indtil for f&#xE5; &#xE5;r siden l&#xE5; der en stor sten i N&#xF6;rre-Lem hede, som kaldtes Simons-stenen og sagdes at v&#xE6;re kastet derhen af en trold p&#xE5; Tylandssiden, som vilde have sl&#xE5;et R&#xF6;dding kirke ned, men den var ham for tung og faldt ude i heden. Folk kl&#xF8;vede efterh&#xE5;nden stykker af den og bortf&#xF8;rte disse, og da Bustrup lade for f&#xE5; &#xE5;r siden afbr&#xE6;ndte ved lynild, brugtes resten af stenen, som kj&#xF6;btes af Bustrup ejer og hjemf&#xF8;rtes af ham til g&#xE5;rden. Der var 30 gode l&#xE6;s. Man kunde i stenen se spor af troldens fingre.</danish_publication>
  <english_publication>Until just a few years ago, there was a large stone out in N&#xF8;rre-Lem heath that was called Simon's stone, and it was said to have been thrown there by a troll over on the Tylland side who wanted to knock R&#xF8;dding church down, but it was too heavy for him and the stone landed out in the heath. After a while, people cleaved pieces off of it and took them away, and when Bustrup barn burned down after a lightning strike a few years ago, the rest of the stone was bought by the owner of Bustrup and brought back to the farm and used to rebuild the barn. It was a good thirty loads. You could see the marks of the troll's fingers in the stone.</english_publication>
